A construction project manager is essential to the effective completion of a building project. A construction project manager's primary duties and competencies include: Planning and scheduling: The project manager is in charge of creating and implementing a precise project plan, which includes schedules, budgets, and resource allocation. They must have good project planning and scheduling abilities, as well as the ability to construct and manage a project schedule utilizing tools like Gantt charts, the critical path method (CPM), and project management software. Cost management: The project manager is in charge of managing costs and ensuring that the project is finished within budget. They must comprehend construction costs and be able to generate accurate budgets as well as manage cost adjustments during the project. Risk management: The project manager is in charge of detecting, analyzing, and managing risks that might jeopardize the project's timeline and budget. They must have great risk management abilities and the ability to create risk management strategies to reduce the effect of possible hazards on the project. Negotiation and communication: The project manager must be able to communicate effectively with all stakeholders, including the owner, design team, subcontractors, and regulatory bodies. They must be able to communicate with all stakeholders to settle any conflicts or difficulties that may occur throughout the project and have outstanding verbal and writing communication skills. Team management and leadership: The project manager is in charge of guiding and inspiring the project team. They must be capable of managing and coordinating the work of the project team, including subcontractors, to ensure that the project is finished on time and within budget. A construction project manager should be well-versed in construction concepts, materials, and processes, as well as safety rules and standards. They should also be familiar with essential building industry norms, regulations, and legislation. To summarize, in order to properly design, execute, and conclude a construction project, a construction project manager must have a mix of technical, management, and leadership abilities. They must be able to balance opposing goals and make choices to guarantee the project is finished on schedule, within budget, and to the owner's satisfaction. 